Extend find command to name status and tag
commitResults.messageBody:
CompanyNameContainsKeywordPredicate.java renamed to
InternShipContainsKeywordPredicate.java. Constructor took in only one
List<String> of keywords for parameter previously. Now, constructor
takes in 3 List<String> parameters, first for company name, second for
status and third for tag.

Find command now can take in n/COMPANY_NAME, s/STATUS and t/TAG. At
least one of these three fields must be present. n/COMPANY_NAME and
s/STATUS should only be used at most once but should they be specified
more than once, only their individual last occurences will be taken.
t/TAG can be specified more than once and will all be taken into
account.

More tests were added to InternShipContainsKeywordPredicateTest.java.

User input was just being parsed into FindCommandParser previously. Now,
it is parsed into the individual ParserUtil functions to ensure that
find commands follow the field constraints.

Updated tests.

When testing equality between FindCommand objects, tagnames did not seem
to be in the order of which they were parsed into parser. This is due to
parseTags using HashSet which orders tagNames automatically in
alphabetic and numeric order. Test was changed accordingly and take note
for future testing.

Use of containsWordIgnoreCase requires the word parameter to not be
empty string which was what was being used in AddressBookParserTest test
case thus causing it to fail. Directly enter lists into
InternshipContainsKeywordPredicate instead of entering strings into
private method that in turn create InternshipContainsKeywordPredicate
object. This will allow for empty lists to be used instead of empty
string being passed into private method which then creates a list of
size 1 with element empty string.

parseCommand_find in AddressBookParserTest was not adhering to the
status and tag input formats of single alphanumeric word.

commitResults.messageBody:
Added new StringUtil method nonZeroUnsignedIntegerCheck() to replace
old method isNonZeroUnsignedInteger(). Old method returned boolean and
could only differentiate between string inputs that represent and don't
represent non-zero unsigned integers. Now, new method returns void.
Throws ParseException objects with different error messages to
differentiate between negative integers and zero, integers with
positive sign and non-integers. If string is non-zero unsigned
integer, method does nothing.

Updated parseIndex in ParserUtil class to use
nonZeroUnsignedIntegerCheck() instead of isNonZeroUnsignedInteger().

Added out of range message in Message class to use when index inputted
is out of range.

Updated EditCommandParser to throw ParserException with out of range
message when index is out of range.

Set Status values as static final strings
commitResults.messageBody:
The format of status is currently not standardised. Eg. New, new, NEW

Let's set internship status values as static final strings.

Other components can import these strings instead of guessing which format
to use.

The delete command deletes internships 1 by 1. The user may want to have
more fine-grained control over delete. Eg, Delete internship entries
belonging to Google.

Delete command now deletes internships that match
all the predicates.
Eg. delete n/google deletes all internships with company name == Google.
Note that the matching is case-insensitive. Filtering is similar to the find
command.
Moreoever, delete can now delete multiple indexes. Eg. delete 1 2.

If predicate and multiple indexes exists, delete first finds all
internships with that indexes. Next, the internships that match
the predicate will be deleted.

Predicate matching is done based on cond1 AND cond2..., instead of
cond1 OR cond2, since OR can be simulated by running multiple delete
commands.

Split delete into delete-field and delete-index
commitResults.messageBody:
Delete command deletes internships based on both index and fields.
The format is delete [index]... [parameters]...
This may be confusing for the user.

We split delete into delete-index and delete-field.
delete-index only delete based on multiple indexes, while
delete-field deletes internships based fields.
Note that both new commands works on the filtered list. ie. delete based on find or
list.

This is much less confusing for the user.
